<worksheet xml:id="week9-handout">
  <title>Week 9 Handout-Numerical Solutions of PDEs- Part 1</title>

    <introduction>
        <statement> <p>
        We will discuss the following topics related to <term> Numerical Methods of PDEs (Chap 16)</term>:
      <ul>
        <li> <p>Week 9: Introduction to Finite Difference (6.5), Laplace Equations (16.1)  </p>   </li>
        <li> <p>Week 10: Heat Equations (16.2), Wave Equations (16.3) </p> </li>
      </ul>  </p>
        </statement>
    </introduction>
    <definition xml:id="def-Taylor-series">
      <title>Taylor Series</title>     
      <statement>
        <p> 
          The Taylor series expansion, centered at a point <m>a</m>, of a function <m>f(x)</m> is
          <md>
            f(x)=f(a)+\frac{f'(a)}{1!}(x-a)+\frac{f''(a)}{2!}(x-a)^2+\frac{f'''(a)}{3!}(x-a)^3+\cdots
          </md>
          Let <m>h=x-a</m>, then the previous equation becomes
          <md>
            f(x)=f(a)+\frac{f'(a)}{1!}h+\frac{f''(a)}{2!}h^2+\frac{f'''(a)}{3!}h^3+\cdots       
          </md>          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <remark>
      <statement>
        <p>The commonly used format of Taylor series is
          <md xml:id="eq-Taylor-general" number="yes">
            f(x+h)=f(x)+f'(x)h+\frac{f''(x)}{2!}h^2+\frac{f'''(x)}{3!}h^3+\cdots
          </md>
          If <m>h</m> is small, the terms involving <m>h^4</m>, <m>h^5, \ldots</m> can be ignored
          (assuming <m>|f^{(n)}(x)|</m> is finite.)          
        </p>
      </statement>
    </remark>
    <definition xml:id="def-finite-deference">
      <title>Finite Difference Methods</title>     
      <statement>
        <p>From <xref ref="eq-Taylor-general"/> we can derive the following approximations:
          <ul>
            <li><p> <term>Forward Difference:</term> <m>f'(x)\approx \frac{1}{h}\left[f(x+h)-f(x)\right]</m>      </p>   </li>
            <li><p> <term>Backward Difference: </term> <m>f'(x)\approx \frac{1}{h}\left[f(x)-f(x-h)\right]</m>      </p>   </li>
            <li><p> <term> Central Difference for 1st order derivative: </term> 
              <md xml:id="eq-central-1st" number="yes">
              f'(x)\approx \frac{1}{2h}\left[f(x+h)-f(x-h)\right]
            </md>  </p>  </li> 
            <li> <p> <term> Central Difference for 2nd order derivative: </term>  
            <md xml:id="eq-central-2nd" number="yes">
              f''(x)\approx \frac{1}{h^2}\left[f(x+h)-2f(x)+f(x-h)\right]
            </md>
                </p> </li>

          </ul>
          This process is also called <term>discretization</term> since we focus on finding 
          values of the solution on <term> discrete points</term>, instead of an explicit formula 
          of the entire domain. This often provides more flexibility when simulating more
          realistic scenario. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p> Consider a linear 2nd order boundary value problem
        <md>
          u''+P(x)u'+Q(x)u=f(x), u(a)=\alpha, u(b)=\beta
        </md>
        Use Finite Difference Method to solve for <m>u(x)</m> over <m>[a,b].</m> 
        Then build the programs in Python and test the correctness of the programs. 
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p> Given the following differential equations and their analytic solutions, 
        find the errors between the numerical solutions from finite difference 
        method and the analytic solution and construct graphs to show errors over <m>[a,b].</m>
        <ol>
          <li> <p> <m>u''+3u'+2u=0,u(1)=1,u(2)=6</m>; <m>u(x)=\frac{1}{e-1}\left[e^{3-2x}-6e^{4-2x}-e^{1-x}+6e^{3-2x}\right]</m>   </p>  </li>
          <li><p> <m>u''+2u'+u=5x,u(0)=0,u(1)=0</m>; <m>u(x)=-10+5x+10e^{-x}+5xe^{1-x}-10xe^{-x}</m>      </p> </li>
          <li><p> <m>x^2u''-xu'+u=0,u(1)=5,u(2)=0</m>; <m>u(x)=5x-5x\log_2(x)</m>  </p></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <definition xml:id="def-laplace-eq">
    <title>Laplace's Equation</title> 
    <statement>
      <p> <md xml:id="eq-laplace-eq" number="yes">
       \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2}=0
      </md>
      
        
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
          <figure xml:id="irregular-shaped-plate">
          <caption align="center">An Irregular shaped plate.</caption>
            <image width="50%" alignment="center">
              <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]

                  % -------------------------------------------------
                    % COLORS
                  % -------------------------------------------------
                  \definecolor{regioncolor}{RGB}{245,215,215}
                  \definecolor{outercolor}{RGB}{210,230,250}

                  % -------------------------------------------------
                    % GRID
                  % -------------------------------------------------
                  \draw[step=1cm,gray!60] (0,0) grid (7,7);

                  % Axes
                  \draw[->] (-0.3,0) -- (7.4,0) node[right] {$x$};
                  \draw[->] (0,-0.3) -- (0,7.4) node[above] {$y$};

                    % Tick labels
                  \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6}
                  \node at (\x,-0.3) {\small $\x h$};
                  \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4,5,6}
                  \node at (-0.3,\y) {\small $\y h$};

                  % -------------------------------------------------
                    % REGION R (inner shape)
                  % -------------------------------------------------
                \begin{scope}
                \fill[regioncolor, fill opacity=0.55]
                  (1,1) .. controls (0.5,2.5) and (0.8,5.5) .. (2,6.5)
                        .. controls (3,7) and (5.2,6.8) .. (6,6)
                        .. controls (6.5,5) and (6.7,3) .. (6,2)
                        .. controls (5,0.8) and (3,0.3) .. (2,0.5)
                        .. controls (1.5,0.7) and (1.1,0.8) .. (1,1)
                    -- cycle;
                \end{scope}

                % Label R
                \node at (3.5,4) {$R$};

                  % -------------------------------------------------
                  % OUTER REGION C
                  % -------------------------------------------------
                  \draw[outercolor, very thick]
                        (1,1) .. controls (0.5,2.5) and (0.8,5.5) .. (2,6.5)
                              .. controls (3,7) and (5.2,6.8) .. (6,6)
                            .. controls (6.5,5) and (6.7,3) .. (6,2)
                            .. controls (5,0.8) and (3,0.3) .. (2,0.5)
                            .. controls (1.5,0.7) and (1.1,0.8) .. (1,1)
                              -- cycle;

                      % label C
                      \node at (6.3,6.3) {$C$};

                      % -------------------------------------------------
                      % POINTS P_{ij}
                      % -------------------------------------------------
                      % black points
                      \foreach \x/\y/\name in {
                            1/3/P_{13},
                            1/2/P_{12},
                            1/1/P_{11},
                            3/1/P_{31}
                            } {
                          \fill (\x,\y) circle (2.8pt);
                          \node[right] at (\x,\y) {\small $\name$};
                          }

                        % red points
                          \foreach \x/\y/\name in {
                          2/2/P_{22},
                          2/1/P_{21}
                            } {
                          \fill[red] (\x,\y) circle (3pt);
                          \node[right] at (\x,\y) {\small $\name$};
                          }

                  \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            </figure>
    <definition xml:id="def-Central-2D">
      <title>Central Difference in 2D</title>  
      <statement>
        <p> <md>
          <mrow  xml:id="eq-central2-x" number="yes">   
                    \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial x^2} \amp\approx \frac{1}{h^2}\left[u(x+h,y)-2u(x,y)+u(x-h,y)\right]</mrow>
          <mrow xml:id="eq-central2-y" number="yes"> 
            \frac{\partial^2 u}{\partial y^2} \amp\approx \frac{1}{h^2}\left[u(x,y+h)-2u(x,y)+u(x,y-h)\right]</mrow>                 
        </md>         
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  <remark>
    <statement>
      <p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-grid-points-2d">
          <caption align="center">Five-Point Approximation.</caption>
            <image width="50%" alignment="center">
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2, every node/.style={font=\small}]
                  %---------------------------
                  % Parameters
                  %---------------------------
                  \def\L{1.5}   % half-extent of grid drawing
                  \def\s{1.0}   % grid spacing = h (unit)
                  \tikzset{
                    gridline/.style={gray!70, line cap=round},
                    pointopen/.style={draw, circle, inner sep=0pt, minimum size=4.5pt, line width=0.6pt, fill=white},
                    pointred/.style={circle, inner sep=0pt, minimum size=4.5pt, fill=red!80!black},
                  }

                  %---------------------------
                  % Grid (3x3 around the center)
                  %---------------------------
                  % vertical lines
                  \foreach \x in {-1,0,1} {
                    \draw[gridline] (\x,-\L) -- (\x,\L);
                  }
                  % horizontal lines
                  \foreach \y in {-1,0,1} {
                    \draw[gridline] (-\L,\y) -- (\L,\y);
                  }

                  %---------------------------
                  % Points
                  %---------------------------
                  % Open circles at neighbors
                  \node[pointopen] (pup)  at (0,  1) {};
                  \node[pointopen] (pdown)at (0, -1) {};
                  \node[pointopen] (pright)at ( 1, 0) {};
                  \node[pointopen] (pleft) at (-1, 0) {};
                  % Red center point
                  \node[pointred]  (pc) at (0,0) {};

                  %---------------------------
                  % Labels for points
                  %---------------------------
                  \node[above right=1pt] at (pup)   {$P_{i,j+1}$};
                  \node[below=2pt]       at (pdown) {$P_{i,j-1}$};
                  \node[right=2pt]       at (pright){$P_{i+1,j}$};
                    \node[left=2pt]        at (pleft) {$P_{i-1,j}$};
                  \node[above=2pt]       at (pc)    {$P_{ij}$};

                  %---------------------------
                  % Dimension arrows for h
                  %---------------------------
                  % Horizontal h (above the top horizontal line)
                  \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1,1.25) -- (0,1.25)
                    node[midway, above=2pt] {$h$};


                  % Vertical h (left of the left vertical line)
                  \draw[&lt;-&gt;] (-1.25, 0) -- (-1.25,1)
                    node[midway, left=2pt] {$h$};

                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        At every point <m>P_{ij}=(x_i,y_j)</m>, we can approximate the Laplace's Equation 
        <xref ref="eq-laplace-eq"/> using central difference (<term>5-point approximation</term>):
        <md>
          <mrow> \amp \frac{\partial^2 u(x_i,y_j)}{\partial x^2}+\frac{\partial^2 u(x_i,y_j)}{\partial y_j} </mrow>
          <mrow>\approx \amp \frac{1}{h^2}\left[u(x_{i+1},y_j)-2u(x_i,y_j)+u(x_{i-1},y_j)\right] </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp +\frac{1}{h^2}\left[u(x_i,y_{j+1})-2u(x_i,y_j)+u(x_i,y_{j-1})\right] </mrow>         
        </md>
      For simplicity, we denote <m>u(x_i,y_j)=u_{i,j}</m>. Then we can rewrite <xref ref="eq-laplace-eq"/>  
        at <m>(x_i,y_j)</m> as
        <md>
          \frac{1}{h^2}\left[u_{i+1,j}+u_{i-1,j}+u_{i,j+1}+u_{i,j-1}-4u_{i,j}\right]=0
        </md>
        
      </p>
    </statement>
  </remark>
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>Solve the Laplace's equation with the following boundary value conditions using
        central difference with the mesh size of <m>h.</m>
        <md>
          <mrow>u(0,y)=0, \amp u(4,y)=y(3-y), 0\lt y\lt 3 </mrow>
          <mrow>u(x,0)=0, \amp u(x,3)=x(4-x),0\lt x\lt 4 </mrow>
        </md>
        
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</worksheet>

